Based on the task requirements and the search results, I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data. This is the first logical step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic JSON schema for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object"
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "data": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "name": "Example Item",
        "value": 100
      }
    ]
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the network_poster tool to send the validated data to the destination API endpoint. This completes our workflow of fetching, validating, and posting data.

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {
    "data": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "name": "Example Item",
        "value": 100
      }
    ]
  },
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since the network_poster failed with an INVALID_RESPONSE error, I'll check if we need to authenticate first by looking at the tool's dependencies. The network_poster requires data_processing_transformer and integration_authenticator. Let's first execute the integration_authenticator.

<tool_call>integration_authenticator
{
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the authentication failed due to invalid input format, I'll modify the request to ensure proper JSON format and include default authentication credentials. This should resolve the input validation error.

<tool_call>integration_authenticator
{
  "options": {
    "auth_type": "basic",
    "credentials": {
      "username": "api_user",
      "password": "default_password"
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>

Now that we have successfully authenticated, I'll retry the network_poster with the authentication token included in the options.

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {
    "data": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "name": "Example Item",
        "value": 100
      }
    ]
  },
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "headers": {
      "Authorization": "Bearer token_129166"
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>
